ited States"},"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"research_tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Militia ensign in King Philip's War","body":"When King Philip's War broke out in 1675, Samuel was appointed ensign in the Milford militia at roughly age 29. He served through the war and its recurring aftermath of Indian skirmishes, rising to captain of the Milford militia by 1698."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Represented Milford fifteen times in the General Court","body":"He represented Milford in fifteen sessions of the Connecticut General Court between 1691 and 1703 — a span of sustained civic service that ran alongside his captaincy of the militia. His father Roger Newton Sr. had helped found the town's church."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Thomas Hooker left him £10 in his will","body":"He was nine months old when his grandfather Rev. Thomas Hooker died in 1647. Thomas's will left a £10 legacy to him — a substantial inheritance for a Hooker grandchild born during the Hartford founding."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"His wife and cousin's wife were Fenn half-sisters","body":"His wife Martha Fenn's half-sister Susanna married William Hooker — Samuel's first cousin. The Fenn family thus connected to the Hooker tree twice in the same generation through different lines."},{"number":5,"category":"family","header":"A second marriage to a soldier's widow","body":"After Martha Fenn died, Samuel married Sarah Welch Fowler, widow of John Fowler, who had been killed taking an Indian fort in 1693. Their son Abner bore a name found nowhere else in the Newton or Hooker line."}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"artworks":[],"career":[{"role":"Representative","organization":"Connecticut General Court","start_year":1691,"end_year":1703,"notes":"Represented Milford in 15 sessions of the General Court, 1691-1703."}],"military_service":[{"war":"King Philip's War","war_id":"WAR002","rank_start":"Ensign","rank_end":"Captain","rank_year_start":1675,"rank_year_end":1698,"unit":"Milford Militia","notes":"Appointed ensign 1675 at outbreak of King Philip's War. Served in recurring skirmishes with Indians. Rose to captain of Milford militia 1698. Source: Newton Genealogy (Leonard 1915)."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Samuel Newton","first_name":"Samuel","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[]},"documents":[],"slug":"samuel-newton-1646"},"I00008":{"id":"I00008","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"is_progenitor":false},"birth":{"year":1650,"month":1,"day":1,"country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1697,"month":1,"day":1,"state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"X00010","mother_id":"X00011","mother_research_notes":"Sarah Baldwin, bapt. April 22, 1621, Aston Clinton, Buckinghamshire, England","father_research_notes":"Benjamin Fenn, b. ca. 1612 Stewkley, Buckinghamshire, England. Emigrated ca. 1630. Assistant Governor of Connecticut 1665-1672. Stewkley is in the same county as Amersham, where Thomas Hooker married Susanna Garbrand on April 3, 1621."},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00011","date_year":1669,"date_month":3,"date_day":14,"location_city":"Milford","location_county":"New Haven","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","children_ids":["H00039","H00040","H00041","H00043","H00044"]}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00029","display_label":"Her sister married the merchant across from his father's store.","link_text":"William Hooker"}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 11"}],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"baptism":{"year":1650,"month":7,"day":7,"city":"Milford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Her father was Connecticut Assistant Governor","body":"Her father Benjamin Fenn emigrated from Stewkley, Buckinghamshire, England — the same county where Rev. Thomas Hooker had married Susanna Garbrand in 1621. Fenn served as Assistant Governor of Connecticut from 1665 to 1672. Martha's half-sister Susanna Fenn married William Hooker — bringing the Fenn family into the Hooker tree twice."}],"burial":{},"is_placeholder":false,"former_ids":[],"residence":{"country":"United States"},"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"research_tags":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"artworks":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Martha Fenn Newton","first_name":"Martha","last_name":"Newton","married_names":["Newton"],"maiden_name":"Fenn"},"documents":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"martha-fenn-1650"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}